```
const originalString = "This is a very long string that needs to be encoded";
const encodedString = btoa(originalString);
console.log(encodedString);
```
This will output a Base64-encoded string that is safe for use in URLs.

To decode the string, you can use the `atob` function:
```
const decodedString = atob(encodedString);
console.log(decodedString);
```
This will output the original string.

Note that the `btoa` and `atob` functions are not part of the standard JavaScript library, but are supported by most modern browsers. If you need to support older browsers, you can use a polyfill or a library that provides these functions.

Also, keep in mind that Base64 encoding can increase the length of your string, so you may want to consider using a different encoding algorithm if you need to keep the length of the encoded string as short as possible.

